In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = new Window(new AppShell());

        window.Created   += (s, e) => Log("Created");
        window.Activated += (s, e) => Log("Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Log("Deactivated");
        window.Stopped   += (s, e) => Log("Stopped");
        window.Resumed   += (s, e) => Log("Resumed");
        window.Destroying += (s, e) => Log("Destroying");
        // Visibility (desktop platforms)
        window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Log("Backgrounding");

        return window;
    }

    static void Log(string evt)
        => System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine($"[Window] {evt} @ {DateTime.Now:T}");
}
```

**Lifecycle order (typical):**

| Transition | Events fired |
|---|---|
| App launch | `Created → Activated` |
| Sent to background | `Deactivated → Stopped` |
| Returned to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |
| App closed | `Destroying` |

**Tips:**
- `Backgrounding` fires on **iOS/macOS** when the app enters the background and lets you save state via `BackgroundingEventArgs.State`.
- On desktop (Windows/macOS), `Stopped`/`Resumed` map to minimize/restore.
- Use `Debug.WriteLine` so output appears in the **Debug Output** window without affecting release builds.
